It must be supposed that the electiori was made by that part of the Roman people which lived at Constantinople (whence claudian calls the Byzantines Quirites) and confirmed by the whole peoplc. And the Roman people preserved no small monument of its right, in the pre- rogatives of the city, in the honour of the consulship, and in other things. And therefore all the right that those who lived at Con- stantinople had to elect the Roman Emperor, depended on the will of the People of Rome. And when the Byzantines had, contrary to the desire and practice of the Roman people, elected a woman, Irene, to the empire, to omit other reasons, the Roman people revoked that concession, express or tacit, and elected an emperor itself 3 aud de- clared its election by the voice of its First Citizen, that is, its Bishop*;
